Observation Details: We assisted in the rescue of this bird. It had become tangled in fishing line in a tree by lake 7. A fisherman noticed it and climbed the tree to try to free it. When we arrived he had just reached it, but could only cut the line allowing the bird to fall to the water. Luckily it was able to paddle to shore where we were able to scoop it up and free it from the monofilament that was tightly wrapped around its wing. Once all the line was removed, we were able to determine that the tangled wing was not seriously injured, just an abrasion could  be seen. When we released it, it flew about 50 feet along the surface of the water and swooped up into a willow to preen.

Observation Details: *My coolest experience yet with Belted Kingfishers. Incredible time spent with a family of two adults and 4 (!) juveniles. The juveniles were the same size as the adults, but I was generally able to tell the adults from the youngsters by behavior, as well as the spotting on the juveniles' plumage on the upperparts. With a close look the juveniles have some orange mixed in the blue of the upper band/belt, giving it a darker appearance. Up close the immature birds plumage also has scalloping on the breast band.  I didn't see any bird attempt to dive for a fish, and the juveniles would perch and look around for 10+ minutes at a time. The juvenile birds were quieter than the adults but did call when flying, usually silent on a perch.  Once I got lucky and had a juvenile perch in a snag next to me.  New high count for Norfolk County!

Excellent views of wintering first year male showing well and calling frequently along the River Darwen around 53.755457, -2.608742. The bird began calling at around 08:15 as it got light and was first seen perched high in an Ash tree albeit rather distantly. The bird eventually moved closer and showed well.   This bird has been present in the area since 8th November ranging between Brockholes Lancashire Wildlife Trust Reserve, Withnell Fold and from 20th December the current site on the River Darwen.   There have been five records of this species in Britain and four in Ireland as follows:  United Kingdom -  2018 - St. Mary's, Isles of Scilly, 18th April, male. 2005 - Tixall, Staffordshire 1st April then Eastrington Ponds, Yorkshire 2nd April then Peterculter, Aberdeen, 4th-8th April. 1st summer male. 1980 - Dundrum Bay, County Down, 12th October, female shot. Oct 12 1979 - Sladesbridge, Cornwall, 2nd October 1979 until June 1980 and Boscathnoe Reservoir, Penzance 23rd to 29th August. Adult male. 1908 - River Allen, Sladesbridge, Cornwall. Female, shot.  Southern Ireland -  2012 - Lough Fee and Kylemore Abbey, County Galway, 5th-6th October, 1st year male. 1985 - Killaloe, County Tipperary, 6th February to 21st March. Female. Same as 1984 bird. 1984 - Ballyvaughan, County Clare,  28th October to early December. Female. Same as 1985 bird. 1978 - Bunree River, near Ballina, County Mayo, 10th December 1979 until 3rd February 1979 when shot. First-winter female.

Observation Details: Excellent views of wintering first year male showing well and calling frequently along the River Darwen around 53.755457, -2.608742. The bird began calling at around 08:15 as it got light and was first seen perched high in an Ash tree albeit rather distantly. The bird eventually moved closer and showed well.   This bird has been present in the area since 8th November ranging between Brockholes Lancashire Wildlife Trust Reserve, Withnell Fold and from 20th December the current site on the River Darwen.   There have been five records of this species in Britain and four in Ireland as follows:  United Kingdom -  2018 - St. Mary's, Isles of Scilly, 18th April, male. 2005 - Tixall, Staffordshire 1st April then Eastrington Ponds, Yorkshire 2nd April then Peterculter, Aberdeen, 4th-8th April. 1st summer male. 1980 - Dundrum Bay, County Down, 12th October, female shot. Oct 12 1979 - Sladesbridge, Cornwall, 2nd October 1979 until June 1980 and Boscathnoe Reservoir, Penzance 23rd to 29th August. Adult male. 1908 - River Allen, Sladesbridge, Cornwall. Female, shot.  Southern Ireland -  2012 - Lough Fee and Kylemore Abbey, County Galway, 5th-6th October, 1st year male. 1985 - Killaloe, County Tipperary, 6th February to 21st March. Female. Same as 1984 bird. 1984 - Ballyvaughan, County Clare,  28th October to early December. Female. Same as 1985 bird. 1978 - Bunree River, near Ballina, County Mayo, 10th December 1979 until 3rd February 1979 when shot. First-winter female.

The Belted Kingfisher I first observed was on a branch overhanging the river. As so often happens, when I drew parallel to it, it dropped from the branch and flew upriver ahead of me. This repeated a couple of times.  Eventually I lost track of it. When I peeked into a little cover where I had seen a family of Wood Ducks last year and a single one today, the kingfisher arrived noisily just before I was about to leave. It was followed a few minutes later by what seemed to be its mate, who disappeared behind a mass of vines along the steep bank near a small culvert. I waited several minutes for the second kingfisher to reappear, but it did not. My view of the first kingfisher was often partially obscured by the leaves of a downed tree when the current gently shifted my position.

Observation Details: *My coolest experience yet with Belted Kingfishers. Incredible time spent with a family of two adults and 4 (!) juveniles. The juveniles were the same size as the adults, but I was generally able to tell the adults from the youngsters by behavior, as well as the spotting on the juveniles' plumage on the upperparts. With a close look the juveniles have some orange mixed in the blue of the upper band/belt, giving it a darker appearance. Up close the immature birds plumage also has scalloping on the breast band.  I didn't see any bird attempt to dive for a fish, and the juveniles would perch and look around for 10+ minutes at a time. The juvenile birds were quieter than the adults but did call when flying, usually silent on a perch.  Once I got lucky and had a juvenile perch in a snag next to me.  New high count for Norfolk County!

This pair of kingfishers is nesting in a vertical sand bank and entering the cavity with fish regularly. At one point, the female arrived with a 5-inch channel cat and flew to a distant branch, the male following her excitedly. She proceeded to schwack the heck out of the fish until a wound appeared on the fish's neck, and it was clearly not moving. But that didn't stop her schwacking. She schwacked until the head was hanging on by only a thread of skin and then eventually, it flipped off the body and dropped into the water. It took her a long time to maneuver the body neck first and then, gulp it down. Then she perched quietly on the branch with a very thick-necked appearance for awhile, apparently not needing to go fishing again for a bit.

The resident female Belted Kingfisher seemed to be making the most out of the cordoned off shoreline and lack of fisherman to hunt.  There was a large eucalyptus branch in the water that she was initially hunting from which is much more out in the open that I usually see her.  She flew past us where we could not see her and the excitement started when a second Belted Kingfisher flew to the area where she was at.  I heard the rattling and commotion and next thing I see is both kingfishers come together and land in the water.  They both flew off but the second kingfisher flew across the lake and all I could see was the back so I couldn't tell if it was another female or a male.  That was the highlight of our trip!
